Considering [this `.designspace`](https://github.com/ctrlcctrlv/Noto-Sans-Tagalog/blob/f73914a8fa0620059a15fc101310e51f8b359033/NotoSansTagalog.designspace#L11) excerpt:

```xml
    <rule name="ra_crossing">
      <conditionset>
        <condition name="weight" minimum="625" maximum="700"/>
      </conditionset>
      <sub name="uni170D" with="uni170D.avar"/>
    </rule>
```

And [this OTLayout feature](https://github.com/ctrlcctrlv/Noto-Sans-Tagalog/blob/f73914a8fa0620059a15fc101310e51f8b359033/features.fea#L50):

```fea
# Ra to archaic Ra
feature hist {
  lookup hist_1 {
    sub uni170D by uni171F;
  } hist_1;
} hist;
```

Why, when `hist` is active, does a `wght` &ge; 625 cause `uni170D`, shaped to `uni171F`, to become `uni170D.avar`?

To confirm that this bug exists, open https://ctrlcctrlv.github.io/baybayin/ , type <kbd>ra</kbd> as input, tick "Archaic _ra_" checkbox, and increase weight above 625.

As part of #1910 I'm about to do some major surgery on building contextual pos/subs. The basic idea is that there are multiple strategies (format 1 / format 2 / format 3) for laying out the subtables, and the task is to organise the rules into subtables forming the most efficient grouping.

Now the question comes when there are explicit subtable breaks in the rules. Should we respect those when grouping? I would imagine the answer is yes, but I am looking at `Tests/feaLib/data/PairPosSubtable.fea` and `Tests/feaLib/data/PairPosSubtable.ttx`. I would expect this to make four subtables:

```
lookup kernlookup {
    pos A V -34;
    subtable;
    pos @group1 @group2 -12;
    subtable;
    pos @group1 @group3 -10;
    pos @group3 @group2 -20;
    subtable;
    pos @group4 @group1 -10;
    pos @group4 @group4 -10;
} kernlookup;
```

In reality, it reorders the rules into three subtables:

```
<!-- SubTableCount=3 -->
```

Is that correct? If so, then the task is to organise the rules into compact subtables regardless of what the user asks for; if not, then I need to respect subtable breaks when grouping the rules.

While documenting feaLib.ast, I came across these signatures:

```python
class SingleSubstStatement(Statement):
    def __init__(self, glyphs, replace, prefix, suffix...):

class LigatureSubstStatement(Statement):
    def __init__(self, prefix, glyphs, suffix, replacement...):

class MultipleSubstStatement(Statement):
   def __init__(self, prefix, glyph, suffix, replacement...):

class ChainContextPosStatement(Statement):
    def __init__(self, prefix, glyphs, suffix, lookups...):

class ReverseChainSingleSubstStatement(Statement):
    def __init__(self, old_prefix, old_suffix, glyphs, replacements, ...):
```

This is horrible. Arguably, this is also horrible:

```python
class PairPosStatement(Statement):
    """``glyphs1`` and ``glyphs2`` should be `glyph-containing objects`_.
    ``valuerecord1`` should be a :class:`ValueRecord` object;
    ``valuerecord2`` should be either a :class:`ValueRecord` object or ``None``.
    """
    def __init__(self, glyphs1, valuerecord1, glyphs2, valuerecord2,
                 enumerated=False, location=None):

class SinglePosStatement(Statement):
    """``pos`` should be a list of (`glyph-containing object`_,
    :class:`ValueRecord`) tuples. There should probably be only one entry in
    that list."""
    def __init__(self, pos, prefix, suffix...):
```

We should fix this, but after #1917 is merged.

In the following lookup, the lookup flag will be ignored which is different from FDK. In FDK it's not ignored.
```fea
    lookup rlig_arab_0 {
        lookupflag RightToLeft IgnoreMarks;
        script arab;
        sub arAlef arLamPF.i arLamPF.m arHehPF.f by arAllah;
    } rlig_arab_0;
```
But if I move the flag after the script statement, it will be taken:
```fea
    lookup rlig_arab_0 {
        script arab;
        lookupflag RightToLeft IgnoreMarks;
        sub arAlef arLamPF.i arLamPF.m arHehPF.f by arAllah;
    } rlig_arab_0;
```
This is not a major issue as long as the user knows about this difference. I had a situation that I couldn't find an explanation why my lookup flag is ignored in fontmake but not in makeotf.
